Nobody98¶

Loan Eligibility Predictor¶

Python Pandas, Sklearn, yellowbrick¶

sklearn.datasets loan data¶

August '22¶

Project Brief:¶

Dream Housing Finance company deals in all home loans. They have presence across all urban, semi urban and rural areas. Customer first apply for home loan after that company validates the customer eligibility for loan. Company wants to automate the loan eligibility process (real time) based on customer detail provided while filling online application form. These details are Gender, Marital Status, Education, Number of Dependents, Income, Loan Amount, Credit History and others. To automate this process, they have given a problem to identify the customers segments, those are eligible for loan amount so that they can specifically target these customers.

# searches for the numeric data/columns with NANs and fills the hole with their modes.

num_cols = train.select_dtypes(include="number").columns

for col in num_cols:
    mode = train[col].dropna().mode()
    if col in test.columns:
        test[col].fillna(mode,axis=0, limit=None,inplace=True)
    elif col in train.columns:
        train[col].fillna(mode,axis=0, limit=None ,inplace=True)

# fills the remaining NaS using padding

null_cols = []

        null_cols.append(cols)

for col in null_cols:
    train[col].fillna(method="pad",axis=0, inplace=True)
    if col in test.columns:
        test[col].fillna(method="pad",axis=0, inplace=True)

Correlation summary

  • There is weak positive relationship between education and applicant income
  • Male applicants were somewhat more likely to be married; a weak positive relationship. Additionally, there is a weak positive relationship between the loan amount and being married.
  • Applicants with good a credit history were moderately more likely to be approved than applicants who don't
  • There is weak negative correlation between the incomes of the applicant and the coapplicant

A more detailed summary of the relationships will be in the profile report

Metrics¶
writing functions to calculate classification metrics to test the effectiveness of the models on training data. The first function returns a dictionaru of the accuracy score, the precision score, confusion matrix and a classification report. The second function prints out each metric from the dictionary.



















In [22]:



     


def scores(model):
    '''Defines the metrics that the models will be using. Returns a dictionary with four sets of metrics'''
    global x_test, y_test
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true = y_test, y_pred= model.predict(x_test))*100
    precision = precision_score(y_true = y_test, y_pred= model.predict(x_test))*100
    classfication = classification_report(y_true = y_test, y_pred= model.predict(x_test))
    confusion = confusion_matrix(y_true = y_test, y_pred= model.predict(x_test))
    return {"Accuracy Score":accuracy, "Precision Score": precision, "Classification Report": classfication, "Confusion Matrix":confusion}

def print_results(results):
    '''This function takes the results from the scores function and prints out the result from each classification metric'''
    keys = results.keys()
    for key in keys:
        print(f'{key}: \n{results.get(key)}\n')

Classification result analysis¶
NB: The models were not tuned, so default parameters were used.


    

  • A result I was not expecting... All the models; XGBoost, Random Forest, Decision Tree and Logistic regression had the exact same performance. Maybe it's the whole "We're all Ensemble models" thing.
    • 

  • The model has an 84% precision score; the model was correct in 107 out of the 127 times that it predicted an applicant would be approved for a loan. 
    • 

  • The model predicted loan rejections with a 93% precision (25 out of 27 correction rejection predictions).
    • 

  • The model had an overall accuracy score of 85%; It made 132 out 154 correct predictions on whether the applicant would be rejected or approved for a loan.
    • 

  • The models are not great at detecting rejections; slightly better than a coin toss (Recall is 56%), 
    • 

  • The models are great at detecting positives; with a 98% recall, the models detected positives nearly perfectly. This may be due to the fact that the training data was unbalanced (support is unbalanced in the classification report, the values should be closer to one another) - see heading on "Checking data distribution". 
    • 

  • The confusion matrix shows that the models were more confused when it comes to false positives, there are 20 false positives; again, this may be because of the unbalanced support (70% of the testing data was positive). 
    •

Soft deployment¶
Gets creates 'main'-like user engagement function (called get_loan() ) and a background method (called predictor()) to store, process the user input and give out the prediction























predictor() function¶
I create a function which takes user-input and returns the prediction. I also overload the predictor() function to also accept a dictionary instead of just user-input; for demostrative purpose (It got tiring having to give user-input with every run)



















In [45]:



     


@dispatch()
def predictor():
    """This function will take user input in order to come up with an observation, stores the user input in a dictionary,
    reshapes the observation so that xgboost does not shout at us, uses the xgboost model results to make a preciction
    and results an array with the binary response; 0 if the loan is declined and 1 if it is approved"""
    time.sleep(2)
    slowprint('\nOh lovely!!\n\nI am going to let you know whether you qualify for a loan.\n\nPlease input the following information for me; And try to follow instructions:\n', 0.5)
    gender = int(input("Please input 1 for male and 0 for female:\n"))
    assert gender in [1,0], 'You failed to follow instructions :('
    
    married = int(input('Please type 1 for "married" or 0 for "not married": \n'))
    assert married in [1,0], 'You failed to follow instructions :('
    
    dependents = int(input("How many dependents do you have?: \n"))
    assert isinstance(dependents, numbers.Number), 'You failed to follow instructions :('
    
    education = int(input("Please input 1 if you have tertiary qualifications and 0 if you do not: \n"))
    assert education in [1,0], 'You failed to follow instructions :('
    
    self_employed = int(input("Please input 1 if you are self-employed, and 0 if you are not self-employed: \n"))
    assert self_employed in [1,0], 'You failed to follow instructions :('
    
    income = float(input("Please input your annual dollar income. Just the number, no currency: \n"))
    assert isinstance(income, numbers.Number), 'That income makes no sense. You have to start over :('
    
    coapplicant_income = float(input("Please input your co-applicant's income. Just the number, no currency: \n"))
    assert isinstance(coapplicant_income, numbers.Number), "You're single aren't you? Is that why you're making up numbers?"
    
    loan_amount = float(input("Please input the loan amount you are seeking in thousands \n e.g. input 5 if you need 5,000. Just enter the number, no currency:\n"))
    assert isinstance(loan_amount, numbers.Number), "You're single aren't you? Is that why you're making up numbers? Do you even need this loan?"
        
    loan_term = int(input("How long do you need to repay the loan? Please pick from the following available terms in months \n[360, 180,  36, 300, 480, 240, 120]: \n"))
    terms = [360, 180,  36, 300, 480, 240, 120]
    assert loan_term in terms, 'Where on earth did you get that number?'
    
    credit_history = int(input("Do you have credit history? Please input 1 for Yes and 0 for No: \n"))
    assert credit_history in [0, 1], "You were so close to finishing without f-ing up. oh well!!"
    
    property_area = int(input("What kind of area do you reside in? Input 0 for rural, 2 for urban or 1 for semi-urban: \n"))
    assert property_area in [1,0, 2], 'You failed to follow instructions. Should I add an option for the moon perhaps? :('

    my_dic = {'Gender': gender, 'Married': married, 'Dependents': dependents, 'Education': education, 'Self_Employed': self_employed,
       'ApplicantIncome': income, 'CoapplicantIncome': coapplicant_income, 'LoanAmount': loan_amount,
       'Loan_Amount_Term': loan_term, 'Credit_History': credit_history, 'Property_Area': property_area}
    
    return model_boost.predict(pd.Series(my_dic).array.reshape(1, -1))

@dispatch (dict)
def predictor(my_dic):
   '''Overloading the method to also accept a dictionary with the inputs'''
   return model_boost.predict(pd.Series(my_dic).array.reshape(1, -1))



     























Loan Application responses¶

In [46]:



     


# creates witty responses to loan applications
# get_loan() will randomly pick one of these responses depending on result of the application

negative_response = ["Yeah no we're not giving you money. Thanks for trying tho!", "Loan declined :(", "Fortunately, we have decided not to burden you with debt", "Unfortunately we have decided not to proceed with the loan. Ya broke!", "You are too poor to be asking us for money. Go away!", "Congratulations! You are going to stay broke!", "Management decided to halt giving out loans literally two seconds ago :("]
positive_response = ["Congratulations!! we have decided to give you a bunch of money...!!", "Loan approved! Congratulations!", "Fine. You can have our money!", "Unfortunately, we have decided to give you a bunch of debts!", "Yay!! Your loan was approved. Don't come for more!", "You're rich enough to associate with us!!", "We're happy to approve your loan!"]



     























get_loan() function¶
get_loan() function acts as the user interface, gets the user input, gives loan application results and prompts whether they would like to make another loan application.



















In [47]:



     


def get_loan ():
    print(90*"=")
    print(31*" ",'Welcome to the Bank of Loans!!\n',90*"=", '\n', sep = "")
    query = int(input('Do you want to apply for a loan? Input 1 for yes, or 0 for No: \n'))
    assert query in [1, 0], "Something went wrong. Dafuq did you do?"   
    if query == 0:
        print("Well that's disappointing! You probably also disappointed your parents didn't you?!? :)", f"\n\n{25*' '}Well Byyeeeee!!!")
    elif query == 1:
        while query == 1: 
            prediction = predictor()[0]
            print("Processing loan application ", end='')
            slowprint(".....", 3)
            if prediction == 1: 
                slowprint(random.choice(positive_response), 1)
                print(90*'=')
                query = int(input('Do you wish to apply for another loan? Input 1 for yes, or 0 for No: \n'))
                assert query in [1, 0], "Something went wrong. What on God's earth did press?" 
            else: 
                slowprint(random.choice(negative_response), 1)
                print(90*'=')
                query = int(input('Do you wish to apply for another loan? Input 1 for yes, or 0 for No: \n'))
                assert query in [1, 0], "Something went wrong. It's probably your fault, my code is flawless" 
              



     























Example¶






















This is the loan application of sub-urban married man with 2 kids. He is as graduate and earns $ 500,000 from his corporate job. Mr Guy's wife earns $ 25,000. The family needs a $ 10,000 loan to pay for their teenage daughter's tuition and accomodation to be repaid over 10 years. He has solid credit history from purchasing his house years earlier. This info is contained in the dictionary below.
